Scope of the Standard

Shunyaya Structural Irreversibility Layer (SSIL) defines a deterministic structural governance layer regulating continuation admissibility across irreversible boundaries.

SSIL establishes:

Finite irreversibility classification:

R = {R0, E0, I1, I2, C}

Conservative collapse invariant:

phi((m,a,s,r)) = m

Deterministic bounded horizon:

H >= 1

Deterministic recovery predicate:

Recovery_H(t)

EdgeZero predicate:

EdgeZero_H(t)

Continuation admissibility mapping:

IRR_ADM(t) ∈ {CONTINUE, ABSTAIN}

Replay identity discipline:

B_A = B_B

SSIL does not:

• modify physical laws
• redefine domain equations
• alter measured magnitude
• introduce predictive models
• simulate future states
• perform optimization
• inject control authority
• guarantee safety outcomes

SSIL governs continuation admissibility — not causation.


Conformance

An implementation conforms to the SSIL Open Standard if it:

Preserves magnitude exactly:

phi((m,a,s,r)) = m

Maintains finite irreversibility regime closure:

R = {R0, E0, I1, I2, C}
|R| = 5

Uses deterministic bounded horizon evaluation H.

Implements deterministic recovery and EdgeZero predicates.

Implements continuation mapping:

IRR_ADM(t) ∈ {CONTINUE, ABSTAIN}

Produces byte-identical artifacts under independent replay:

B_A = B_B

Avoids probabilistic or tolerance-based arbitration.

Any implementation introducing:

• randomness
• probabilistic inference
• adaptive thresholds
• predictive extrapolation
• tolerance-based comparison
• nondeterministic output
• runtime regime expansion

does not conform to the SSIL Open Standard.

Independent implementations are permitted and encouraged.


